13_plot_coterminal_rads


  1. Question

    An angle measure, \(\theta\), equals \(\frac{-62\pi}{11}\) radians. A second angle measure, \(\phi\), is coterminal to \(\theta\), and \(0\le\phi<2\pi\). Which graph shows \(\phi\) in standard position?



    1. A
    2. B
    3. C
    4. D
    5. E
    6. F
    7. G
    8. H

    Solution

    The given angle measure is \(\theta=\frac{-62\pi}{11}\) radians. Because the given angle is less than 0, repeatedly add \(2\pi\) until getting a coterminal angle between 0 and \(2\pi\). It should be mentioned that \(2\pi = \frac{22\pi}{11}\), so we can add fractions with common denominators.

    \[\frac{-62\pi}{11}+\frac{22\pi}{11}=\frac{-40\pi}{11}\] \[\frac{-40\pi}{11}+\frac{22\pi}{11}=\frac{-18\pi}{11}\] \[\frac{-18\pi}{11}+\frac{22\pi}{11}=\frac{4\pi}{11}\]

    We found the coterminal angle \(\phi=\frac{4\pi}{11}\). I prefer to think of this as \(4\) times \(\frac{\pi}{11}\), so then I imagine the top semicircle (and bottom semicircle) broken up into 11 equally-spaced wedges.

    6. F
    7. G
    8. H

    Solution

    The given angle measure is \(\theta=\frac{62\pi}{11}\) radians. Because the given angle is more than \(2\pi\), repeatedly subtract \(2\pi\) until getting a coterminal angle between 0 and \(2\pi\). It should be mentioned that \(2\pi = \frac{22\pi}{11}\), so we can add fractions with common denominators.

    \[\frac{62\pi}{11}-\frac{22\pi}{11}=\frac{40\pi}{11}\] \[\frac{40\pi}{11}-\frac{22\pi}{11}=\frac{18\pi}{11}\]

    We found the coterminal angle \(\phi=\frac{18\pi}{11}\). I prefer to think of this as \(18\) times \(\frac{\pi}{11}\), so then I imagine the top semicircle (and bottom semicircle) broken up into 11 equally-spaced wedges.
